-- 
U.S. Stock Futures Rise Before Payrolls Report; Kraft Advances

-- B y   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 
2011-05-06T10:13:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-06/u-s-stock-futures-rise-before-employment-report-kraft-gains-on-earnings.html
U.S. stock futures rose, indicating
the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index may pare its biggest weekly
decline in five months, as investors awaited the government’s
monthly payrolls report.  Kraft Foods Inc. (KFT)  advanced in  Germany  after earnings
exceeded analyst estimates.  Freeport-McMoRan Copper & Gold Inc. (FCX) 
slid as commodities extended their selloff.  S&P 500  futures expiring in June rose 0.3 percent to
1,339.1 at 11:12 a.m. in London after the gauge slid 0.9 percent
yesterday. Dow Jones Industrial Average futures gained 0.2
percent to 12,594, while futures on the Nasdaq-100 Index
increased 0.3 percent to 2,386.75.  “After yesterday’s sharp drop, stocks could be due a
bounce this morning,” said  Manoj Ladwa , a senior trader at ETX
Capital in London. Through “traders are likely to treat any
rally with caution” before the U.S. jobs figures.  Today’s payrolls report is forecast to show the pace of
hiring in the world’s largest economy cooled in April as
companies curbed spending in the face of rising raw-material
costs, according to economists.  Payrolls rose by 185,000 workers last month compared with a
216,000 advance in March, according to the median economist
forecast in a Bloomberg News survey. The jobless rate may have
held at 8.8 percent. The data is due at 8:30 a.m. in  Washington .  Labor Department figures yesterday showed applications for
jobless benefits jumped by 43,000 to 474,000 in the week ended
April 30, the most since August.  Weekly Decline  The S&P 500 has lost 2.1 percent so far this week as metal
prices tumbled and crude oil slumped below $100 a barrel amid
concern about the strength of the global economic recovery. The
gauge has still risen 6.2 percent in 2011, driven by government
stimulus measures and higher than-estimated corporate earnings.  Earnings-per-share beat estimates at 73 percent of the 413
companies in the S&P 500 that reported results since April 11,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Kraft increased 0.6 percent to $33.58 even as the world’s
second-largest food company lowered its full-year earnings
forecast. The maker of Oreo cookies and Cadbury chocolate
reported first-quarter adjusted profit of 52 cents a share,
beating the 47-cent average of analyst estimates compiled by
Bloomberg.  Freeport-McMoRan, the largest publicly traded copper
producer, lost 0.4 percent to $49.66 in German trading.  Commodities fell for a fifth day, extending the biggest
rout since December 2008, as investors cut their holdings in
oil, silver and industrial metals amid concern that economic
growth will slow.  The S&P GSCI Index of 24 raw materials tumbled as much as
3.6 percent. The gauge has fallen 11 percent this week, the
biggest drop since 2008. Crude slumped 5.2 percent, silver 3.8
percent and copper 1 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Sarah Jones in  London  at 
